1 Experimental Setup

Comparison of proteome between porcine pancreatic ductal organoids of different passages and donor ages. Organoids were derived from Embryonic, early postnatal and adult animals and cultured. For the early postnatal derived organoids, early and late passages were used to isolate proteins and investigate proteomic differences.

4.2 Filtering of missing values

Code 
data_filter <- filter_se(data_se, thr = 1, fraction = 2/12)
filter base on missing number is <= 1 in at least one condition.
filter base on missing number fraction < 0.166666666666667 in each row
Code

6 Selecting Imputation Method

Code 
set.seed(09051997)

6.1 Missing at Random or not at random

Are the missing values missing randomly dispersed through the data, or is missingness more of a feature because the different samples acquire different trajectories and hence different proteomes. Here, it is more MNAR (missing not at random), a lot of proteins are either present in Organoids of early passage or late. Missingness correlates with sample condition and is not at random.

6.2 MNAR vs.Â MAR

Code 
data_norm %>% plot_missval()

7 Impute

Imputation Using Gsimp seems most appropriate to keep variance similar to Unimputed values. Deep Learning based imputation using the random gibbs sampler embedded in the GSIMP function.

imps <- assay(data_imp) %>% data.frame %>% gather("label", "value") %>% 
      left_join(colData(data_imp)[c("label","condition")],copy = T) %>%

## Missing at Random or not at random

Are the missing values missing randomly dispersed through the data, or is missingness more of a feature because the different samples acquire different trajectories and hence different proteomes.
Here, it is more MNAR (missing not at random), a lot of proteins are either present in Organoids of early passage or late. Missingness correlates with sample condition and is not at random.

## MNAR vs. MAR

```{r}
data_norm %>% plot_missval()

```


# Impute
Imputation Using Gsimp seems most appropriate to keep variance similar to Unimputed values. 
Deep Learning based imputation using the random gibbs sampler embedded in the GSIMP function.

```{r}
data_norm %>% DEP2::impute(. , fun = "GSimp", hi_q = 0.1,
                       iters_each=100, iters_all=20) -> data_imp
```
# Imputation


```{r fig.width=10}
NAs <- is.na(assay(data_norm)) 
## the imputed values by different methods.
imps <- assay(data_imp) %>% data.frame %>% gather("label", "value") %>% 
      left_join(colData(data_imp)[c("label","condition")],copy = T) %>%
      magrittr::extract(as.vector(NAs),)%>% mutate(method = "GSimp")



nonimps <- assay(data_norm) %>% data.frame %>% gather("label", "value") %>%
  left_join(colData(data_norm)[c("label","condition")],copy = T) %>% 
  magrittr::extract(!as.vector(NAs),) %>% mutate(method = "non_imputed") %>%
  dplyr::select(method,everything())

ggplot(rbind(imps, nonimps),aes(x = value,y = factor(method,level = unique(method)))) + 
  geom_density_ridges(fill = "#ff506e", scale = .91,
                      jittered_points = TRUE,position = position_points_jitter(height = 0),
                      point_shape = '|', point_size = 2, point_alpha = 1, alpha = 0.7) +
  ylab("Impute method")+ xlab("Log2 value") + 
  theme_cowplot()+ggtitle("Distribution of imputed Values")
```


# Testing significant differences between conditions

BH correction of pval for multiple testing 

```{r}
data_imp %>%  test_diff(type = "all", control = "Embryo", fdr.type = "BH") %>%
    add_rejections(alpha = 0.05, lfc = 1) -> data_test# alpha is the significance level, lfc is the log fold change threshold

```
